1 \\pmod{16}\\).\nThe modular inverse of \\(5\\) modulo \\(16\\) is \\(13\\) because \\(5 \\cdot 13 = 65 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{16}\\).\nThe modular inverse of \\(7\\) modulo \\(16\\) is \\(7\\) because \\(7 \\cdot 7 = 49 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{16}\\).\nThe modular inverse of \\(9\\) modulo \\(16\\) is \\(9\\) because \\(9 \\cdot 9 = 81 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{16}\\).\nThe modular inverse of \\(11\\) modulo \\(16\\) is \\(3\\) because \\(11 \\cdot 3 = 33 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{16}\\).\nThe modular inverse of \\(13\\) modulo \\(16\\) is \\(5\\) because \\(13 \\cdot 5 = 65 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{16}\\).\nThe modular inverse of \\(15\\) modulo \\(16\\) is \\(15\\) because \\(15 \\cdot 15 = 225 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{16}\\).\n\nNow, we sum these inverses:\n\\[1 + 11 + 13 + 7 + 9 + 3 + 5 + 15\\]\n\nWe can simplify the addition step by step:\n\\[1 + 11 = 12\\]\n\\[12 + 13 = 25 \\equiv 9 \\pmod{16}\\]\n\\[9 + 7 = 16 \\equiv 0 \\pmod{16}\\]\n\\[0 + 9 = 9\\]\n\\[9 + 3 = 12\\]\n\\[12 + 5 = 17 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{16}\\]\n\\[1 + 15 = 16 \\equiv 0 \\pmod{16}\\]\n\nThus, the residue modulo \\(16\\) of the sum of the modulo \\(16\\) inverses of the first \\(8\\) positive odd integers is \\(\\boxed{0}\\).\n\nEvaluate as indicated, simplified completely. $f'(3)|_{f(x)= \\sqrt{x} +1}$\nTo evaluate \\( f'(3) \\) for the function \\( f(x) = \\sqrt{x} + 1 \\), we need to follow these steps:\n\n1. **Find the derivative of \\( f(x) \\):**\n\n   The function given is \\( f(x) = \\sqrt{x} + 1 \\). We can rewrite \\(\\sqrt{x}\\) as \\( x^{1/2} \\).\n\n   \\[\n   f(x) = x^{1/2} + 1\n   \\]\n\n   Now, we apply the power rule for differentiation, which states that if \\( g(x) = x^n \\), then \\( g'(x) = n x^{n-1} \\).\n\n   For \\( x^{1/2} \\):\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( x^{1/2} \\right) = \\frac{1}{2} x^{1/2 - 1} = \\frac{1}{2} x^{-1/2}\n   \\]\n\n   For the constant term \\( 1 \\):\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d}{dx} (1) = 0\n   \\]\n\n   Therefore, the derivative of \\( f(x) \\) is:\n   \\[\n   f'(x) = \\frac{1}{2} x^{-1/2}\n   \\]\n